### 🐍 Option 3: Python Rendering Example

You can also try rendering a basic 3D scene using Python. You'll need to install dependencies first:

```bash
pip install trimesh matplotlib
```

Example snippet:

```python
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.axis("off")

# Simple cube vertices (representing a house side)
cube_vertices = np.array([
    [-2, -2, 0], [2, -2, 0], [2, 2, 0], [-2, 2, 0]
])

for i in range(3):
    j = (i + 1) % 3
    x_start, y_start, _, x_end, y_end, _ = cube_vertices[i], cube_vertices[j], 0, None

def draw_3d_line(ax, v1, v2, color='black'):
    ax.plot([v1[0], v2[0]], [v1[1], v2[1]], color=color)

axes = plt.gca()
draw_3d_line(axes, cube_vertices[0], cube_vertices[1])
draw_3d_line(axes, cube_vertices[1], cube_vertices[2])
draw_3d_line(axes, cube_vertices[2], cube_vertices[3])
draw_3d_line(axes, cube_vertices[3], cube_vertices[0])

plt.title("Basic 3D House Shape (2D Projection)")

plt.show()
```

📌 Note: This generates a 2D projection for illustration purposes—not true 3D rendering. Use Three.js or Blender for full 3D visuals.

